4th Street, at, and adjoining the N.E. corner of 27th Avenue, showing two old mansions. The corner house (right) was owned by J. Laroque in 1873, and the other by L. J. White. The latter was also known as the Homer Whittemore house, according to E. L. Armbruster. View 3 shows the Whittemore house only. These homes appear in Wolverton's atlas of 1891, but ownership is not indicated.

27th Ave., south side, east from 4th Street. The Astoria Presbyterian Church, whose congregation was organized in 1846, laid the cornerstone of this church on November 30th of the same year. In 1848 it was dedicated to the service of God; and in 1857 was enlarged. Rev. Stead was at one time its rector. The church was demolished in 1928 and buildings Nos. 4-14 to 4-24 are on the site. However, the Beers Atlas of Long Island does not show a church on this site in 1873.

4th Street, east side, at 27th Avenue. The house on the right is at the S.E. corner of the intersection and is on the former property of the Astoria Presbyterian Church, whose place of worship stood in rear of the house. The house to the left, at the N.E. corner, with the cupola, was the house of J. Laroque in 1873. The third house was owned by L. J. White in 1873. These houses do not appear in Beers's 1873 atlas of Long Island; the authority for the above data being E. L. Armbruster. View 2 shows the S.E. corner house.
